AB  - Through the Kyoto Protocol, Romania is committed to reduce greenhouse gas emissions. The Protocol defines three mechanisms that can be use by the parties involved in the Protocol. International Emissions Trading (IET) is one of these three mechanisms. Thus, countries with a surplus of allowances that are available could sell their CO2 emissions to countries with a deficit.
   Having a surplus of available allowances, Romania could trade them to other parties, such as OECD countries, with a deficit. Selling these emissions, the Romanian state could collect up to two billion euros, annually, and the money could be invest in other projects, in order to reduce emissions, further more.
   The aim of this article is to enhance the contribution to the development of a methodology for calculating greenhouse gas emissions, from the perspective of the forestry land structure. Firstly, the article will focus on the description of the forestry land composition, from the perspective of the species and the groups of species it includes, highlighting the importance of certain forest species in mitigating polluting factors in the atmosphere, through a certain specific analysis. Secondly, we will try to identify those arguments that support the harmonization of the methodology for calculating greenhouse gas emissions with the particularities that derive from the structure of the forestry land.
   In this way, our work suggests that the contribution of certain species can be significantly higher in reducing of the greenhouse gas emissions, even though Romania does not have such a large forest area as other European countries (for example, Sweden). Hence, the financial advantages that Romania receives from trading of emissions could be much greater, than those that have been estimate at present.
