AB  - Contemporary safety thinking is saturated with cultural ideas. Culture is presumed important-for safety. Culture has become part of the convention, the normal scientific approach to understand and improve safety. It is part of the standard toolbox in terms of explanatory and interpretive repertoire. But, what is the nature of the culture conceptions? How is culture "applied" in terms of interpretations and explanations? Pursuing such questions, this paper identifies conceptions of culture by conferring source material pertaining to the Norwegian petroleum industry (official documents and an incident investigation reports). The analysis was performed by establishing a set of analytical dimensions or thematic axes: The What, The How, The Where, and The Who of safety culture. The results of these analyses are discussed. The core thesis of this paper is that the premises, presumptions, and implications of a given concept need active consideration. And, in a mode of efficient application, there is a danger of merely pointing towards "culture", and omitting the necessary "detour" of specifying suppositions and implications involved in the given cultural concept. This underscores the need to actively "apply" theory (Storseth and Grotan, 2011). By addressing issues of theoretical underpinnings and presumptions concerning association, function and causality-a needed, additional layer of analysis and learning as application (Baumard, 1999; Storseth and Tinmannsvik, 2013) is forced into consideration, bringing awareness to the "directions" that silently influence interpretive and explanatory efforts to understand and improve safety.
