AB  - A crucial aspect in environmental sciences is related to the transportation, accumulation and fate of solid organic pollutants. Coal-derived particles originating from mines, as well as from processing and power plants, tend to disseminate over long distances either as air- or water-borne material, and finally precipitate and mix with sediments and/or the topsoils. By applying organic-petrography methods, discrimination between natural and anthropogenic solid-organic residues can be achieved.
   In this study we present the petrographical features of seven samples obtained from lake sediments from Sweden, Finland and The Netherlands. Most of the samples represent the uppermost layers, which accumulated during the recent past. Their total organic carbon content ranges between 1.5 and 20%. Density separations using heavy liquids were applied, in order to concentrate the organic matter and thus to facilitate the petrographical determinations. The organic-matter fraction of each sample was embedded with epoxy resin and prepared for microscopic examination.
   The microscopic approach is based on the maceral nomenclature applied for coals. In each sample, 500 organic particles (i.e., macerals) were determined. The maceral features revealed significant variations on the origin and hence, the type of the contained organic matter. Apart from the modern plant debris contained in the surface sediments, and the algae indicating water-saturated conditions, several "more mature" humic material, as well as artificially oxidized organic particles were identified. In other words, some of the samples correspond to blends of naturally and artificially derived solid-organic material. The latter constitutes organic pollutants, which include unburnt residues of high-rank coals identified as vitrinites, and oxidized tissues referred to as chars. The sample that contained the higher percentage of vitrinites and chars originates from a heavily industrialized area. Huminite, which represents the humic fraction of plant-derived remnants, includes the predominant organic tissues in most of the samples, with values ranging between 40-80 vol.-% on dry, mineral matter-free basis (dmmf). Vitrinite was identified in various amounts, and particularly in one sample its content reaches up to 40 vol.-% (dmmo indicating the intense pollution of the respective area. Liptinite that corresponds to hydrogen-rich plant remnants like lipids, cuticles, waxes, spores and algae, ranges from 2-51 vol.-% (dmmg. Inertinite, which includes the oxidized (naturally or artificially) organic particles, shows values between 1-21 vol.-% (dmmf]l. The quantification of the solid organic contaminants is relatively easy under the microscope with the limitation of the grain size (> 5 mu m). Hence, significant information can be obtained regarding the trace and mapping of the contamination impact in certain areas.
