AB  - This paper focuses on the possibilities of using satellite data for detecting and quantifying vegetation changes and the distribution of changes caused by an increased exploitation of the Swedish mountains. The methods outlined in this study are to give a basis for change detection of less sustainable mountain ecosystems by using lichen cover as indicator. Digital image analysis, Landsat 5 TM data, hyperspectral imaging scanner data and digital terrain models were used to study mountain vegetation in two test sites located, one in the southern part and one in the northern part of the Swedish mountains. The results show that mountain vegetation can be classified with good results into 12 classes with emphasis on dwarf shrub heath vegetation using Landsat TM data. The changes in lichen cover have been detected using lichen index differentiating technique. By estimation of the biomass of lichens using vegetation indices, Landsat TM data, can be used to map a decrease in lichen cover in 2 classes: 20-30% and 50-60%. The result is based on possibilities to differentiate "lichen cover" in 3 classes: high > 80%, moderate 50-80% and low 20-50%.
