AB  - This paper describes on-going research efforts addressing the impacts of the European Waste Electrical and Electronic Equipment Directive. The present stage of the implementation of the Directive in Finland is discussed, and the WEEE recovery potential of Oulu region is outlined. It is presented that to prevent waste, we need to know the reasons of why electronic equipment became waste. This key question is analysed using a novel waste taxonomy. Development efforts and future research needs for mobile phone recovery, are summarized. Finally, a conceptual model of Waste Electrical and Electronic Equipment is introduced. This descriptive model describes patterns of waste generation and the state-of-the-art of its treatment. It is argued that this waste management model would perform as a producer responsibility support tool to aid enterprises in internalising environmental issues. It is asserted that continued research-industry-administrative collaboration is needed to build a sustainable WEEE recovery infrastructure.
